The number of triangles (\(K_3\) subgraphs) in a complete graph \(K_n\) can be computed using the combination formula \( \binom{n}{3} \), which counts the number of ways to choose 3 vertices from \(n\) vertices. 

For \( n = 8 \):

\[ \binom{8}{3} = \frac{8!}{3!(8-3)!} = \frac{8!}{3!5!} = \frac{8 \times 7 \times 6}{3 \times 2 \times 1} = 56 \]

Therefore, the number of triangles in the graph is [56].
